There seems to be a general tendency in Roman law to favour, in the' earlier periods, the assessment os damages ac- cording to the verum rei pretium, andin the later to substitute the alternative method. By Cod. 7. 47 Justinian enacted that in actions on contract the damages recoverable as ‘interesse’ by the plaintiff should never be more than double the verum rei pretium
